          "body": "The chapter's pivotal theological move is the 'But now' of verse 4. David could not build because wars surrounded him on every side (5:3). Solomon can build because the LORD has given him rest (*nuach*) on every side, with no adversary (*satan*) and no misfortune (*pega*, 5:4). This is not accidental vocabulary. Deuteronomy 12:10-11 had promised that when the LORD gives His people rest from their enemies, they will bring their offerings to 'the place the LORD your God will choose.' 2 Samuel 7:1 notes that the promise of a Temple-builder was first given to David precisely when 'the LORD had given him rest from all his enemies.' The rest-and-build sequence is the canonical pattern. Solomon reads his political situation as a theological indicator: peace is not a coincidence but an invitation. The era of warfare has served its preparatory purpose; the era of construction has arrived. Wise leadership discerns the season it occupies."
