          "body": "The chapter closes without ceremony — no dedication, no prayer, no theophany. Just timber and stone being cut, shaped, and readied (5:18). This is the chapter's quiet pastoral point: faithful preparation is itself an act of obedience. Solomon did not wait for a second vision or a supernatural confirming sign before activating the Davidic promise. He read the political conditions (rest, no adversary), remembered the divine word (5:5), made the necessary alliances (5:12), mobilized the available workforce (5:13-18), and began. The foundation stones are 'large, costly stones' (*gadol*, *yaqar*, 5:17), meticulously dressed (*gazit*) — expensive effort for stones that will be buried and never seen once the Temple rises. This is the theology of preparation in miniature: the quality of the unseen foundation determines the integrity of what will be visible. Those who build for God are called to excellence at the level no one will ever observe."
